Apart from API automation, I also worked on UI automation using Playwright with TypeScript.
The goal was to ensure that all front-end features were working correctly from a user perspective."

Designing framework using Page Object Model
"I structured the framework using Page Object Model so that locators and actions are separated, which made tests cleaner and easier to maintain."

👉 Writing test cases for critical flows
I automated key user journeys specific to the Everbridge Public Warning Platform, such as creating and sending alert messages, selecting target areas, and verifying message delivery status.
These flows are critical because they directly impact how emergency alerts are broadcast to users.
So I ensured end-to-end validation — from message creation to delivery confirmation — to make sure the system works reliably during real-world scenarios.


👉 Reducing flakiness
"I handled timing issues using Playwright's auto-waiting, proper selectors, and added controlled retry logic for unstable scenarios."
How:?
Yeah, flakiness was a major issue initially, especially in alert workflows where UI depends on backend processing.
For example, after sending an alert in the Everbridge system, the UI status doesn't update immediately — it goes from Pending → Processing → Delivered asynchronously.

Earlier, tests were failing randomly because they were checking the status too early.
So what I did was:

👉 Instead of just relying on UI wait, I aligned UI validation with backend behavior.

await page.waitForResponse(resp =>
  resp.url().includes('/alerts') && resp.status() === 200
)

await expect(page.locator('#status')).toHaveText('Delivered')


👉 Creating reusable methods
"I created common utility methods for repeated actions like login or navigation, so we avoid duplication and keep tests simple."

👉 Improving debugging
"I added proper logging and structured tests clearly, so when a test fails, it's easy to identify the issue quickly."

⚡ Ultra Short Version
👉
"Structured framework, automated key flows, reduced flakiness, reused code, and improved debugging."


Why Playwright
"Playwright was useful because:
	• it supports auto-waiting
	• faster execution
	• better handling of modern web apps compared to older tools"


Impact
"This helped in:
	• catching UI issues early
	• reducing manual testing effort
	• ensuring end-to-end flows were validated"

"I improved UI test stability and maintainability by restructuring the framework and reducing flakiness."


